<p>To answer these important questions about Ginger Ale, I had to dig into the drinkâ€™s roots â€” itâ€™s fresh ginger roots that is (ğŸ¥ ). Ginger is one of the worldâ€™s oldest-traded vegetables. Over the last several centuries, traders have moved it across the world and, most relevant for this story, across Western Africa. With ginger firmly rooting itself around the world, the vegetable became cheaper and commonplace within traditional medicine. In many West African communities, ginger was a common remedy for inflammation and upset stomachs.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, like most stories about â€œWhy is X like this in America?,â€ hereâ€™s where we learn how slavery is likely the foundation to this storyâ€™s answer. During the era of the transatlantic slave trade, enslaved Africans forced to the Americas had non-existent to at best grotesquely inadequate health care access. In most cases, captives health care options were:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Treat yourself using herbal remedies passed down from your elders</li>
  <li>Physicking â€” a practice where those who held people in slavery used the equivalent of a WebMD article to self-diagnose their captive and then would try and perform the recommended procedure on them directly (with no training)</li>
</ol>

<p>Needless to say, many enslaved people flocked to traditional medicine and roots such as ginger to treat ailments. By no means were all West African cultural remedies effective, but when put between your ancestorâ€™s remedies and an enslaverâ€™s quizzical live testing, those cultural treatments were the obvious best choice.</p>

<p>Even after the United States finally abolished slavery, health care equity didnâ€™t automatically materialize. (Authorâ€™s note: 156 years later and that equity still hasnâ€™t arrived. You can review <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/tuskegee/timeline.htm" target="_blank">Tuskegee Syphilis Experiment</a>, <a href="https://vm.tiktok.com/ZMe13GfSb/" target="_blank">Medical professionals only learning diseases on people with Caucasian skin</a>, and <a href="https://vm.tiktok.com/ZMe13GfSb/" target="_blank">Medical professionals only learning diseases on people with Caucasian skin</a> for just a brief sampling of evidence to this point).</p>

<p>So racism was a factor as usual â€” how does soda play in?</p>

<p>Around the start of the 20th century, soda entered the cultural sphere. Originally marketed as health drinks, sodas also have a racist history, something you can read more about in Professor Grace Elizabeth Haleâ€™s <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/29/opinion/when-jim-crow-drank-coke.html" target="_blank">â€œWhen Jim Crow Drank Coke.â€</a>Â  In our case, we skip to 1907, the year John James McLaughlin, a Canadian pharmacist, patented the name Canada Dry. Unlike other ales on the market at the time, Canada Dry had a lighter ginger taste that made it more palatable. That light taste made the drink popular for both kids and also for adults who loved it as a mixer during the Prohibition era. As the prohibition raged on, the company leaned back into the initial medicinal aims of soda, focusing their positioning around the drinkâ€™s ability to alleviate stomach discomfort.</p>

