<p>As soft drink companies continued to grow, their prices not only dropped, but they began to realize the money they were missing not targeting Black communities. Canada Dry and other sods companies began to seek ad space across Black-owned newspapers across the nation as they sought new customers.</p>

<p>My research trail goes partially cold from here. (Authorâ€™s note: You can blame that to the plethora of academic articles and newspaper clippings locked by paywalls.) However, it leads me to my final conclusion I share withy you and what some readers may have skimmed to learn â€” whatâ€™s the story of Ginger Ale becoming so prominent as an elixir in Black community stereotypes?</p>

<h3 id="wills-hypothesis-to-the-rise-of-ginger-ale">Willâ€™s hypothesis to the rise of ginger ale</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Ginger has been at the core of traditional herbal remedies in many cultures, including in West Africa</li>
  <li>As enslaved Africans were forced to the Americas, their limited health care access led them to even further rely upon the remedies they learned from their elders, including ginger.</li>
  <li>As enslaved Africans were â€œfreedâ€, racial healthcare disparities along with medical racism persisted, continuing Black Americans penchance toward herbal home remedies, passing their family go-tos down to subsequent generation.</li>
  <li>Soda companies, originally marketed as health products, rise to the cultural stage in the early 20th century. Brands including Canada Dry at various points over their early decades leaned into the notion of their productsâ€™s health properties as they aggressively expanded across the nation and became more affordable.</li>
  <li>As soft drink companies realized the money they were leaving on the table not targeting the Black community, they began to push their cheap drinks with similar positioning to this community. (Authorâ€™s note: Pepsi was one of the first brands to begin employing Black Americans <a href="https://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/article/how-corporate-america-came-to-recognize-diversity-one-pepsi-at-a-time/" target="_blank">to grow their presence in the community</a>)</li>
  <li>With soda prices becoming incredibly cheap mixed, Ginger Ale was able to successfully penetrate as a go to sick day drink as a result of its a) widespread availability b) better taste compared to real ginger because of the sugar c) longer shelf life than real ginger root. With all these factors, especially itâ€™s sweet taste, it made it easier to quell a childâ€™s upset stomach with less of a fuss.</li>
</ol>

<p>Weâ€™ve finally made it to the end of this long story, but you might be wondering â€œDoes Ginger Ale actually work?â€ Likely not with modern recipes. In fact, Canada Dry, my familyâ€™s Ginger Ale of choice, has been sued several times in recent years over their â€œMade by real gingerâ€ line. In one lawsuit, the defendants noted:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œThey do buy actual ginger, but then what they do is they boil it in ethanol, and that essentially destroys any nutritional or medicinal benefits,â€ Mark Canofari said, adding that Canada Dry uses a ginger concentrate. â€œOne drop fills 70 cans [â€¦] and a drop is .05 ml. So thatâ€™s how little, even of the concentrate, is actually in one drink.â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In many of these cases, Canada Dryâ€™s owners, Keurig Dr. Pepper have <a href="https://www.foodandwine.com/news/ginger-ale-canada-dry-medicine-settlement" target="_blank">settled out of court</a> and the companyâ€™s marketing has begun to shy away from its medical benefits. Based on that, my view is Ginger Ale likely may soothe an upset stomach, but itâ€™s ginger levels are likely too low to have any meaningful health benefits outside of placebo. Nevertheless, the drink has built up a perception so great itâ€™ll likely to maintain its pull for families looking for a quick cold remedy. As for me? Iâ€™ll likely still go for a can when Iâ€™m feeling under the weather â€” maybe not for the health benefits but for the childhood nostalgia it invokes every time I take a sip.</p>
